The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, July 28, 2004 				 Usha Martin, Otis ink deal
 A STAFF REPORTER				 	 Usha Martin chairman B. K. Jhawar (extreme right) in Calcutta on Tuesday. Picture by Kishor Roy Chowdhury 																								Calcutta, July 27: Usha Martin Ltd, the flagship company of the city-based Jhawar group, has grabbed a large order from US-based global elevator major, Otis, to supply speciality wire ropes.																								Disclosing this to newspersons after the companys 18th annual general meeting here today, Usha Martin chairman B. K. Jhawar said the contract has been received after a cut-throat competition with other major wire-rope makers in the world.																								Otis will use the speciality wire rope for its customers in Asia and west Europe, he said.																								The contract has been signed for three years. While refusing to divulge the volume of the contract or the total earnings potential, Jhawar said the supply to Otis will contribute to around 15 per cent of the total wire business.																								The company is also looking at opportunities to supply high-performance mining rope to North America where it has been supplying some quantity of medium level mining ropes.																								Usha Martin has been able to position itself as one of the largest wire rope makers in the world. It is now trying to tap the automobile component manufacturers. The company is in the process of getting the all-required certification that will ensure a smooth entry to the automobile sector.																								Usha Martin has posted a net profit of over Rs 8 crore in the first quarter of the current fiscal compared with Rs 3 crore in the corresponding period last year.																								Turnover has increased to Rs 269.94 crore from Rs 163.23 crore in the year-ago period.																								However, the interest outgo has come down to Rs 17.35 crore in the reporting quarter from Rs 19.03 crore in the comparable previous quarter.
